<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Public Administration Select Committee Inquiry into</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">written evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Government Ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> [PHS0051]</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our previous submissions we focussed upon the three main drivers for reform of the complaints and ombudsman systems- a better service for the public; better value for money; and better for local and Parliamentary accountability.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have identified eight principles that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reflect the needs of the public when they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">seeking an independent review of their complaint, individual redress and systemic improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Increase public awareness and access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Seamless service</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Maximise knowledge and expertise</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Authority to remedy injustice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and require service improvement</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Strong local complaint handling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with independent oversight</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Value for money</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Independent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">corporate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">governance</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Increase scrutiny and accountability of public services locally and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">centrally</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have developed a number of proposals that we believe meet those principles and would deliver a better service, better value for money and better accountability. We hope that the Committee will find these proposals helpful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> informing their future recommendations.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#ccc0d9; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Principle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">- Increase public awareness and access</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n essential pre-requisite is effective access to justice and right to redress for the public. In our previous submissions we highlighted the complexities that are inherent in the ‘complaints maze’. The vast array of routes that the pubic need to navigate when public services let them down means that redress is too often inaccessible.  The following reforms would demystify and simplify access to the ombudsman.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">A single portal for complaints</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As has been the case in Wales, a single portal for complaints about public services could be more effectively promoted and make it easier for people to find their way to the Ombudsman. As with Complaints Wales this could be delivered by a Public Service Ombudsman for England to ensure its independence from government and service providers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Direct access for citizens which still allows for advocates to support the complaint</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Citizens should have direct access to the Ombudsman service whilst still being able to seek support from their councillor, MP or other advocate. This is particularly important for the most vulnerable complainants who wish to remain private.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Statutory requirement for all providers to signpost to the ombudsman</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A statutory requirement for all providers to signpost to the ombudsman, as is the case in the financial and legal sectors, would ensure that the public are aware of their right to complain when services fail and they are not satisfied with local complaints handling.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Broadly drafted statutory eligibility requirements supported by detailed scheme rules</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The public should have the right to a route to redress. Statutory eligibility requirements for bringing a complaint to the Ombudsman would enable the right of all users of public services to seek redress. They should be focussed upon securing the delivery of a free, informal ombudsman service that does not require legal representation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These statutory requirements could be underpinned by more detailed scheme rules published by the Board of the Ombudsman’s Office. These rules would set out in a transparent and accessible way how the ombudsman scheme would operate and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the ombudsman’s office would determine whether to investigate an issue. Such scheme rules would allow the Ombudsman to respond rapidly to changing models of service delivery without needing to seek legislative change to meet the needs of the public.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#ccc0d9; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Principle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">- Seamless service</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Complaints about public services are not confined to administrative or other sector boundaries.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The delivery model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for public services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the exercise of statutory duties and functions continues to change.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A wider range of providers, including the private and third sectors, now deliver services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in fulfilment of the statutory duties of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public bodies. An increasing number of people are receiving public services through multi-agency arrangements. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The administration of services which have been the responsibility of central government departments, such as welfare benefits and health care are also now being devolved to local authorities. This devolved system includes new bodies to support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local accountability and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">complaints handling, such as Healthwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The public should not have to make complex determinations about who is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accountable for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">delivering their service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and therefore liable for redress,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and which Ombudsman can help them when those services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fail.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The proposals we make below have the aim of providing users of all public services in England with a seamless</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, consistent and comprehensive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ombudsman service.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">A single Public Services Ombudsman for England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> single Public Services Ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for England </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould provide people in England with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a unified, consistent and comprehensive service which avoids the current systemic confusion.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">A common business model and service standards</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">People who complain to an Ombudsman need to understand the handling process and what outcome they can expect.  This requires openness and transparency about the service. The creation of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ny new unified service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would require a common business model, performance indicators and quality standards to provide public assurance and understanding.  This could build on the existing experience and expertise of sector specific Ombudsman, for example for local government, social care, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">health.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#ccc0d9; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Principle 3- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Maximise k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nowledge and expertise</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The value of an independent and impartial investigation by the Ombudsman should not be underestimated.  This is equally valuable in highlighting when no fault has occurred as it is in determining fault and injustice which require remedy.  Complainants need to be satisfied that investigations are conducted fairly based on relevant evidence and with a thorough understanding of the proper application of the relevant law, statutory guidance, policy and best </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">practice.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ombudsmen scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> needs to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">demonstrate expertise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in their areas of jurisdiction t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o ensure accurate decision making that users of the service can trust.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">A Public Services Ombudsman operating with lead ombudsmen overseeing complaints about different sectors</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A single public services ombudsman would inevitably have jurisdiction over a wide range of public services. It will be essential for building trust in the quality of decision making that the ombudsman service can demonstrate expertise in those different areas. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mploying lead ombudsmen for different sectors would help to build that trust and would ensure that any new Ombudsman could draw upon the expertise that exists in c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urrent schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#ccc0d9; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Principle 4- Authority to remedy injustice and require service improvement</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If complaints cannot be addressed by the local provider, the public want to know that their complaint will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be investigated by somebody</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with the authority to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">put things right.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The strength of an Ombudsman approach is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authority to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> remedy both the injustice caused to individuals by the actions of public services and to tackle the wider injustices that may occur by requiring service improvements. The current public service ombudsmen all have differ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> powers to aid them in meeting these objectives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clarification of enforcement powers could be achieved as follows: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Power to enforce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">recommendations </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under the current system public bodies usually comply with ombudsmen recommendations.  The sovereignty of the legislature to make decisions concerning policy and the use of public money has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> been maintained. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Both LGO and PHSO report in excess of 99% compliance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. As changes in service delivery bring more independent bodies into jurisdiction, for example all registered social care providers which have been in the jurisdiction of LGO since 2010, the Ombudsman must maintain appropriate authority to achieve compliance.  This would be strengthened by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">discretion to seek judicial enforcement of recommendations. However, this power should be subject to an affirmative instrument before it comes into effect.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Duty to refer to the regulator </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the regulatory landscape of public services, proper arrangements need to be in place to provide a route to redress for individual complaints or groups of complainants.  This is not the role of the regulator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> body</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which has responsibility and authority to ensure systemic change in line with regulatory standards. The ombudsman will however consider compliance with regulatory standards in determining a complaint. The ombudsman and the regulator need to work together to share intelligence, learn from complaints and bring about improvement action.  The LGO works closely with appropriate regulators for social care and education to achieve this.   A duty on the ombudsman to refer concerns to the relevant regulator with a similar duty on the regulator to follow up would strengthen this relationship and provide further public assurance.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#ccc0d9; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Principle 5- Strong local complaint handling with independent oversight</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Members of the public want their complaints resolved as quickly as possible by the body concerned.  Referral to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mbudsm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is a final stage and should only be necessary when local routes for redress have been exhausted. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ombudsman sits at the apex of the system, not only to provide independent and robust oversight when local complaints handling fails, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensure that bodies take responsibility and accountability for their own performance and for resolving complaints. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The role of the ombudsman must also be to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">encourage robust</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local complaint handling. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Duty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">on the Ombudsman </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">to set common standards for complaints handling </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LGO has for nearly 40 years provided informal guidance, advice and training for local councils in support of local complaints handling.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In his evidence to the Committee, the Scottish Public Services Ombudsman highlighted his work in setting common standards for complaints handling through a Complaints Standards Authority.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A statutory duty for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Services Ombudsman for England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would be the appropriate way to formalise and strengthen this role.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Role for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">elevant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> regulators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">audit c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ompliance with common standards</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the Scottish model, Audit Scotland has the role to audit compliance with the standards set by the Complaint Standards Authority. We consider that an arrangement of this nature helps to prevent confusion between the role of an ombudsman and the role of a regulator.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We would recommend that a similar approach is taken in England with relevant regulators such as the National Audit Office and the Care Quality Commission being responsible for auditing compliance with complaint standards set by a Public Services Ombudsman for England.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#ccc0d9; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Principle 6- Value for money</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An ombudsman service must be free of charge to the complainant. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As with any publically funded service, a Public Service Ombudsman for England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should provide value for money. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where a service is publically funded through taxation it follows that the relevant ombudsman scheme should also be publically funded.  However where bodies in jurisdiction are not publically funded </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they should not be funded by the tax payer.  </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Charging model for independent sector providers</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As is usually the case with ombudsman schemes serving the private sector, a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public Services Ombudsman for England should have powers to recover the costs of investigating complaints about non-public bodies from the providers themselves. This could be done by using </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">either a sector wide levy, a case fee for each complaint handled about a provider or a combination of both.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This would reduce the burden on the public purse and help to ensure that all providers are accountable.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#ccc0d9; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Principle 7- Independent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">corporate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> governance</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The public expect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an ombudsman scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndependent of the body complained about.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This is best delivered by a governance structure that can hold the service to account for its performance in an effective and robust manner without fear of being fettered by government or other bodies in jurisdiction. The proposals we make below are informed by recent reviews of our own governance by an External Evaluation and by Robert Gordon. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Governance provided by a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Board</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> for Public Service Complaints</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">- appointed by and accountable to Parliament</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Good governance and accountability comes from strong, independent voices providing challenge and scrutiny.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This can be best achieved by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n independent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Board for Public Service Complaints charged with establishing and overseeing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Public Service Ombudsman Service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Board could in turn be accountable to Parliament through a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">designated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Operation of the Ombudsman Scheme headed by a Chief O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">mbudsman- appointed by and accountable to the Board</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposed Board for Public Service Complaints </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould be responsible for appointing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a Chief Ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in whose authority complaints would be investigated and decided</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to run the Ombudsman Service. The Board would be responsible for managing the performance of the Chief Ombudsman.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#ccc0d9; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Principle 8- Increase scrutiny &amp; accountability of services locally &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">centrally</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public services should be accountable to the people that use them as this is the most effective way of ensuring that those services are respons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the needs of their users. Whilst the public have increasing choice about the services they use democratically elected representatives, locally and nationally,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have an important role to play in ensuring accountability.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Reform of the ombudsman landscape provides an opportunity to enhance scrutiny of public services and make more effective use of complaints in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a consumer democracy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">tatutory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">requirement that Ombudsman findings are considered by full council in local authorities and by Boards in other bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently some local authorities do consider our recommendations in full council and we consider that this scrutiny aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local accountability and helps to ensure that services are accountable to the public through locally elected members. However, this approach is not consistent across local government and so we would recommend including a statutory requirement for local authorities to consider the findings of the Ombudsman in full council.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For other bodies in the Ombudsman’s jurisdiction there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a similar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">statutory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">requirement for the Board of that body to consider findings from the Ombudsman.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Ombudsman </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">has a role to support democratic scrutiny of public services</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The findings of </span><span style="fo